In the apical osculum (Fig. 
2C, E
), there are paired actines of triactines and tetractines, some additional tangential diactines, together forming a clear line dividing the apical oscula, and some radial diactines projecting beyond the apical osculum with different length.

In the sponge body (Fig. 
2C, E
), the triactines and tetractines are regularly arranged, their paired actines are parallel to the apical oscula, and the unpaired actines point downward, with slight folding allowed, but never overlapping; in contrast to the triactines and tetractines, the diactines are arranged more irregularly but generally point downward.

In the root-like structures (Fig. 
2D, F
), the arrangement of triactines and tetractines is the same as that in the body, but the arrangement of diactines is different; most of them tangentially project beyond the surface, which results in the surface having a slightly hispid appearance.
